ownedComment.body: Configuration of which Interrupt line at the NVIC is allowed to create an Interrupt in the M7, i.e. what interrupt are resulting in the execution of the corresponding Interrupt Service Routine

Interrupts are configured in 2 stages:
(1) Within SPIM HW register space the corresponding HW interrupts being enabled/disabled can be configured by means of the ACC-SPIM driver functions. This is very fine granular allowing for configuring all sources of each Interrupt line going to the NVIC.
(2) Within NVIC register space the corresponding M7 Interrupts can be enabled/disabled by means of the NVIC handler functions. This allows for configuring entire interrupt line handling.

For more information about M7 Interrupts and exceptions, refer to (1) ARM Cortex-M7 Devices Generic User Guide https://developer.arm.com/documentation/dui0646/a/the-cortex-m7-processor and (2) ARM Cortex-M7 Processor Technical Reference Manual https://developer.arm.com/documentation/ddi0489/d/programmers-model/system-address-map/private-peripheral-bus
For the type of exceptions please refer to (1) section 2.3.2 Exception types (Ihttps://developer.arm.com/documentation/dui0646/b/the-cortex-m7-processor/exception-model/exception-types?lang=en)
Please note that not all exception an be configured regarding their priority. For example, - Reset: It is permanently enabled and has a fixed priority of -3. - NMI: It is permanently enabled and has a fixed priority of -2 - HardFault: HardFaults have a fixed priority of -1, meaning they have higher priority than any exception with configurable priority.
The following exceptions (i.e. system handlers adn interrupts) are configurable and are handled within this SW unit: - MemManage: A MemManage fault is an exception that occurs because of a memory protection related fault - BusFault: A BusFault is an exception that occurs because of a memory related fault for an instruction or data memory transaction - UsageFault: A UsageFault is an exception that occurs because of a fault related to instruction execution. This includes: - An undefined instruction. - An illegal unaligned access. - Invalid state on instruction execution. - An error on exception return. The following can cause a UsageFault when the core is configured to report them: - An unaligned address on word and halfword memory access. - Division by zero. - SVCall: A supervisor call (SVC) is an exception triggered by the SVC instruction. - PendSV: PendSV is an interrupt-driven request for system-level service. - SysTick: A SysTick exception is an exception the system timer generates when it reaches zero. - Interrupt (IRQ): A interrupt, or IRQ, is an exception signaled by a peripheral, or generated by a software request.
(See (1) Table 2.14. Properties of the different exception types)
